  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Boating Below the澄心 Pavilion at Yangsan, Presented to Saman
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    True appreciation demands we drift upon the water,
    yet wine still clouds the mind in lofty halls.
    By willows, a painted boat lies moored,
    beneath bamboo, the click of go stones echoes.

    Official scribes mingle with gulls and herons,
    distant lanterns now replace the moon and stars.
    As night deepens, still we pole the boat along,
    our robes and shoes glistening with morning dew.
  footnotes:
    - Saman (士廉) likely refers to a distinguished guest or companion of the poet on this occasion.
    - The poem contrasts the lingering effects of wine in the formal setting above with the purifying experience of being on the water.
    - The 'click of go stones' suggests intellectual leisure and refined company during the outing.
    - The final image of dew-glistening robes suggests the night journey has extended through dawn, merging the boundaries between evening entertainment and morning contemplation.
